      "statement is `take i L.flatten = ...`, and `L.flatten = [a, b, c]`, `i = 3`, `take i L.flatten = [a, b, c]`. \n\nHmm, the theorem seems to be false in this case unless `k` is adjusted. \n\nBut perhaps the intended meaning of `j` was that `j + 1` is the first index where partial sum `> i`, but in Lean, when the partial sums do not exceed `i`, it returns `j = 0`, which makes `k = i`, but then `L[j]` is `L[0]`, and taking `i` elements from it may not work unless `L[0]` is long enough. \n\nBut in the case above, `L[0] = [a, b]`, `i = 3`, `k = 3`, `take 3 [a, b] = [a, b]`, `[] ++ [a, b] = [a, b] ≠ [a, b, c]`. \n\nThus, the theorem seems wrong in Lean. \n\nBut perhaps the mistake was in interpreting `j`: in the case when no `partialSum > i`, the correct `j` should be `L.length`, not `0`, because the sum of all sublists' lengths is `≤ i`, and we have to take all of them, and `k = i - sum`.\n\nBut in Lean, when no element",
