      "\n   But in Lean, `(L : List α).findIdx (p : α → Bool)` is the first index where `p a = true` or `0` otherwise. \n\n   So for `(map length L).partialSums = [0]`, `(map length L).partialSums.findIdx (· > i)` is `0` if no element `> i`.\n\n   But for `L = []`, `L.map length = []`, `partialSums = [0]`, so if `i = 0`, then `(0 > 0)` is false, and `findIdx = 0`. Then `j = 0 - 1 = 0`, `k = i - (take j L).flatten.length = 0 - 0 = 0`. The statement becomes `take 0 [] = [] ++ take 0 (L[j]?.getD [])`. But `L[j]?.getD [] = ([] : List (List α)) [0]?.getD [] = none.getD [] = []`, so `take 0 [] = [] ++ []`, correct. \n\n   But `i < L.flatten.length` is false for `i = 0` because `L = []` implies `L.flatten.length = 0`.\n\n   So actually, if `i < L.flatten.length`, then `L ≠ []` and `(L.map length).partialSums = [0, ...]` where the next element is `l₁.length`. \n\n   If `i < l₁.length`, then `(L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (· > i)` is `1`, because `0 > i`? No: `i ≥ 0`, so `0 > i` is false unless `i = 0`, and `0 > 0` is false. The first element `> i` is `l₁.length` (`= 1` if `i = 0`), unless `l₁.length ≤ i`, but if `i < l₁.length`, then `l₁.length > i`. \n\n   So actually, for `i < l₁.length`, `(L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (· > i)` is `2` because `(L.map length).partialSums = [0, l₁.length, ...]`, `0 > i` is false, `l₁.length > i` is true (`i < l₁.length`), so `findIdx = 1`. Thus `j = 1 - 1 = 0`.\n\n   Wait, no: the indices are:\n   `(L.map length).partialSums = [0, l₁.length, l₁.length + l₂.length, ...]`.\n\n   So if `L = [ [a] ]`, `L.map length = [1]`, `partialSums = [0, 1]`.\n   For `i = 0`, `[0, 1].findIdx (· > 0)` is `1` (`0 > 0` false, `1 > 0` true).\n   For `i = 1`, `[0, 1].findIdx (· > 1)` is `0` (no element `> 1`).\n   But `L = [ [a] ]` implies `L.flatten.length = 1`, so `i = 1` is not `< 1`.\n\n   It appears that the previous confusion was due to misunderstanding `List.findIdx`. \n\n   Actually, according to Lean docs:\n   ```\n   List.findIdx : ∀ {α : Type} [BEq α], (p : α → Bool) → List α → ℕ\n   ```\n   `List.findIdx p xs` returns the first index `i` such that `p (xs[i]) = true`, or `0` if no such index exists. \n\n   So in `[0, 1].findIdx (· > 0",
